  "runs": [
    {
      "tool": {
        "driver": {
          "name": "Strix",
          "informationUri": "https://strix.ai",
          "rules": [
            {
              "id": "CWE-639",
              "name": "Unauthenticated User Impersonation in /api/sara/create-project",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Unauthenticated User Impersonation in /api/sara/create-project"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "The `POST /api/sara/create-project` API endpoint accepts a `userId` field from the unauthenticated request body and creates a database record attributed to that user, with no verification that the caller is actually authenticated as that user. Because the handler uses the Supabase **service role key** (which bypasses all Row Level Security policies), any anonymous internet caller can create projects owned by an arbitrary Supabase user UUID."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "The `POST /api/sara/create-project` API endpoint accepts a `userId` field from the unauthenticated request body and creates a database record attributed to that user, with no verification that the caller is actually authenticated as that user. Because the handler uses the Supabase **service role key** (which bypasses all Row Level Security policies), any anonymous internet caller can create projects owned by an arbitrary Supabase user UUID.\n\nAn unauthenticated attacker who knows (or enumerates) a victim's Supabase UUID can flood the victim's project library with arbitrary projects, corrupt their workspace state, and potentially interfere with features that depend on project counts or project IDs. Because the service role key bypasses RLS, this write path has no database-level backstop. If project creation triggers downstream side-effects (webhook calls, storage allocation, billing events), the impact surface expands further.\n\nValidate the caller's identity server-side before using any user identifier:\n\n1. At the start of the handler, retrieve the authenticated session from the request cookies using Supabase's SSR helper (`createServerClient` with `@supabase/ssr`, or `createRouteHandlerClient` with `@supabase/auth-helpers-nextjs`). Return `401 Unauthorized` if no valid session exists.\n2. Derive `userId` exclusively from `session.user.id` — never accept it as a body parameter. If a `userId` field is still included in the body for legacy compatibility, reject the request with `403 Forbidden` when it does not match the session user's ID.\n3. Remove the service role key from this route. Use a session-scoped Supabase client so that RLS policies enforce ownership at the database layer as a defence-in-depth measure.\n4. Remove the hardcoded fallback value for `ANON_KEY` on line 6. Require the environment variable to be explicitly set; fail fast at startup if it is absent.\n5. Rotate the exposed anon key (`sb_publishable_juNeZXupS_SXWtvvK1MdLw_gVRnqhsE`) immediately, as it is now permanently committed to source history.",
                "markdown": "The `POST /api/sara/create-project` API endpoint accepts a `userId` field from the unauthenticated request body and creates a database record attributed to that user, with no verification that the caller is actually authenticated as that user. Because the handler uses the Supabase **service role key** (which bypasses all Row Level Security policies), any anonymous internet caller can create projects owned by an arbitrary Supabase user UUID.\n\nAn unauthenticated attacker who knows (or enumerates) a victim's Supabase UUID can flood the victim's project library with arbitrary projects, corrupt their workspace state, and potentially interfere with features that depend on project counts or project IDs. Because the service role key bypasses RLS, this write path has no database-level backstop. If project creation triggers downstream side-effects (webhook calls, storage allocation, billing events), the impact surface expands further.\n\nValidate the caller's identity server-side before using any user identifier:\n\n1. At the start of the handler, retrieve the authenticated session from the request cookies using Supabase's SSR helper (`createServerClient` with `@supabase/ssr`, or `createRouteHandlerClient` with `@supabase/auth-helpers-nextjs`). Return `401 Unauthorized` if no valid session exists.\n2. Derive `userId` exclusively from `session.user.id` — never accept it as a body parameter. If a `userId` field is still included in the body for legacy compatibility, reject the request with `403 Forbidden` when it does not match the session user's ID.\n3. Remove the service role key from this route. Use a session-scoped Supabase client so that RLS policies enforce ownership at the database layer as a defence-in-depth measure.\n4. Remove the hardcoded fallback value for `ANON_KEY` on line 6. Require the environment variable to be explicitly set; fail fast at startup if it is absent.\n5. Rotate the exposed anon key (`sb_publishable_juNeZXupS_SXWtvvK1MdLw_gVRnqhsE`) immediately, as it is now permanently committed to source history."
              },
              "properties": {
                "security-severity": "7.5",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-639",
                  "stride:E"
                ]
              },
              "helpUri": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/639.html"
            }
          ],
          "version": "1.1.0"
        }
      },
      "results": [
        {
          "ruleId": "CWE-639",
          "ruleIndex": 0,
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "Unauthenticated User Impersonation in /api/sara/create-project\n\nThe `POST /api/sara/create-project` API endpoint accepts a `userId` field from the unauthenticated request body and creates a database record attributed to that user, with no verification that the caller is actually authenticated as that user. Because the handler uses the Supabase **service role key** (which bypasses all Row Level Security policies), any anonymous internet caller can create projects owned by an arbitrary Supabase user UUID."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "app/api/sara/create-project/route.ts"
